clone the directory and have a look:
git clone --recurse-submodules git@github.com:kyriacos/dotfiles.git ~/.dotfiles

(The --recurse-submodules flag pulls in TPM and any other submodules.)

Then run the bootstrap script:
  sh ~/.dotfiles/bootstrap

Running without options does a full setup:
  computer name → gitconfig → dotfiles → shell → Xcode tools → Homebrew → osx defaults → karabiner → tmux plugins

## Bootstrap options

Passing one or more --*-only flags runs only those steps. No flags = full setup.

  --name-only          Set the computer name only
  --gitconfig-only     Set up git config only
  --dotfiles-only      Symlink dotfiles only
  --brew-only          Run Homebrew update/bundle/upgrade only
  --osx-only           Run osx_set_defaults.sh only
  --karabiner-only     Symlink Karabiner config only
  --tmux-only          Install tmux plugins only
  --ass-only           Install ass (AI Session Search) only

Skip flags (full run only):
  --skip-brew          Skip all Homebrew steps
  --skip-osx           Skip macOS defaults setup
  --skip-tmux          Skip tmux plugin installation
  --skip-gitconfig     Skip git config setup

Brew modifiers (apply to full run or --brew-only):
  --name <name>        Set computer name non-interactively (prompts if omitted)
  --skip-mas           Skip Mac App Store apps
  --skip-casks         Skip cask installations
  --formulas-only      Brew formulas only; skip mas, casks, and vscode extensions

Examples:
  bootstrap                              Full setup (prompts for computer name)
  bootstrap --name "Kyriacos MBP"        Full setup, set computer name upfront
  bootstrap --brew-only                  Only run Homebrew
  bootstrap --brew-only --skip-mas       Only run Homebrew, skip App Store
  bootstrap --dotfiles-only              Only symlink dotfiles
  bootstrap --osx-only --tmux-only       Only run osx defaults and tmux setup

All CLI tools are managed via the Brewfile. The bootstrap script runs `brew bundle`
to install everything, including zsh-syntax-highlighting, fzf, ripgrep, fd, and zoxide.

## Local overrides (not tracked)

Put machine-specific settings in files under `$HOME`. They are listed in the global
gitignore and are never committed by any repo on this machine.

| File | When it loads | Use for |
|------|---------------|---------|
| `~/.zshenv.local` | Every zsh session, early (after tracked `~/.zshenv`) | Env vars needed everywhere, including non-interactive shells |
| `~/.localrc` | Interactive shells, mid-`~/.zshrc` (after plugins) | Per-machine aliases, paths, tool config |
| `~/.zshrc.local` | Interactive shells, end of `~/.zshrc` | Late overrides; API keys and secrets |

Example — API key or token:

  # ~/.zshenv.local  (or ~/.localrc / ~/.zshrc.local)
  export OPENAI_API_KEY="sk-..."

Create only the files you need. On first `bootstrap` run (or `--dotfiles-only`),
empty stubs are created for any of the three that do not already exist.

`~/.gitconfig.local` is different: it is symlinked from
this repo (`dots/gitconfig.local`) for shared git settings, not for secrets.

## tmux setup

Install tmux:
  brew install tmux

The bootstrap script symlinks ~/.tmux.conf and ~/.tmux from this repo.
TPM (Tmux Plugin Manager) is included as a git submodule at
dots/tmux/plugins/tpm, so it's available immediately after cloning.

### Layout

  ~/.tmux.conf              entry point (sources ~/.tmux/tmux.conf)
  ~/.tmux/tmux.conf         main config (rose-pine, keybindings, plugins)
  ~/.tmux/bin/              auto-labeling scripts (on PATH)
  ~/.tmux/zsh/              zsh hooks for live label updates
  ~/.tmux/plugins/          TPM and plugins
  ~/.tmux/README            full auto-labeling docs

### Auto-labeling

Window tabs and pane borders show context without manual renaming.

Label priority:
  1. Custom name — prefix+, or `twname my-label` (reset with `twname -r`)
  2. Git repo — `repo-or-worktree · branch` (e.g. backend-feature · fix-auth)
  3. Process — running command (nvim, node, …)
  4. Directory — cwd basename when not in git

Behaviour:
  - Status bar window tab shows the active pane's label
  - Every pane shows its label on the bottom border (bold = active)

Updates on pane/window switch (tmux hooks) and on cd / prompt / command
(zsh hooks). See ~/.tmux/README for script details.

### Plugin install

The bootstrap script runs plugin installation automatically. To install
or reinstall plugins manually:
  ~/.tmux/plugins/tpm/bin/install_plugins

Or from inside tmux:
  prefix + I   (capital I, as in Install)

### Upgrading TPM and plugins

Upgrade TPM (the submodule) to its latest upstream commit:
  cd ~/.dotfiles
  git submodule update --remote dots/tmux/plugins/tpm
  git add dots/tmux/plugins/tpm && git commit -m "Bump TPM to latest"

Upgrade all installed plugins:
  ~/.tmux/plugins/tpm/bin/update_plugins all

Or from inside tmux:
  prefix + U   (capital U, as in Update)

## Cursor chat sync (cursaves)

Install cursaves to sync Cursor AI conversations across machines via a private git repo or S3:

  uv tool install git+https://github.com/Callum-Ward/cursaves.git

Initialize once per machine (point at a private repo):
  cursaves init --remote git@github.com:you/cursaves-data.git

Common commands:
  cursaves sync    # pull behind + push ahead (recommended daily driver)
  cursaves push    # checkpoint + push to remote
  cursaves pull    # pull from remote + import into Cursor's DB

After pull, restart Cursor fully (quit and reopen) to see imported conversations.

## ass (AI Session Search)

Search and replay AI coding sessions (Claude, Cursor, etc.) from the terminal.
Repo: https://github.com/kyriacos/ai-session-search

The bootstrap script installs it automatically. To install manually:

  curl -fsSL https://github.com/kyriacos/ai-session-search/releases/latest/download/ass \
    -o ~/.local/bin/ass && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/ass

Make sure ~/.local/bin is on your PATH (already included in dots/zshrc if using this repo).

